PUH-BrianMartell Metallicity Damping Coefficient _Z  Understandable Explanation Heavy elements (metals) are complex, multi-strand braids in the lattice. The more metallicity Z (fraction of mass in elements heavier than He), the more these braids clog free ripple flow  increasing viscosity/drag on torsional and shear waves. Simple picture:   Pure H/He lattice: Low braid complexity  ripples propagate freely (high phase velocity).   High Z: Heavy braids scatter/deflect ripples  energy dissipates faster (damping).   Coefficient _Z quantifies clogging strength per unit metallicity. Effect: Early universe (low Z)  stiff, fast ripples. Late universe (higher Z)  damped, slower propagation.
